# ADR-005: Community Model

## Status

Accepted

## Date

2026-06-28

## Context

Famm is inspired by the idea that fitness professionals often sit at the center of communities. A trainer may connect clients, friends, gyms, businesses, classes, events, and peer groups.

However, this concept is not limited to fitness.

The broader platform must eventually support communities for:

- Therapists
- Tutors
- Music teachers
- Tattoo artists
- Coaches
- Consultants
- Creators
- Local businesses
- Professional networks
- Peer groups

If communities are modeled as gyms, classes, or trainer groups only, the platform will lose the ability to support broader social commerce use cases.

## Decision

The platform will model communities using a generalized `Community` primitive and community membership relationships.

A community may represent:

- A trainer’s client group
- A gym community
- A class cohort
- A coaching group
- A tutoring group
- A music studio
- A tattoo shop following
- A creator audience
- A professional network
- A local commerce group

The Famm application may use fitness-specific labels, but platform-core should remain industry-neutral.

## Layer

Platform Core

## Platform Primitives Affected

- User
- Organization
- Community
- Relationship
- Activity
- Conversation
- Offer
- Transaction
- Referral
- Event
- ReputationSignal

## Proposed Community Model

The platform community model should support:

```text
community_id
organization_id or tenant_id
name
description
community_type
visibility
status
created_by
created_at
updated_at
metadata
```

The community membership model should support:

```text
community_membership_id
community_id
member_entity_id
member_entity_type
role
status
joined_at
left_at
created_at
updated_at
metadata
```

Example community types:

```text
business_community
provider_community
customer_group
class_cohort
membership_group
creator_audience
professional_network
local_group
```

Example community roles:

```text
owner
admin
moderator
provider
member
guest
```

## Alternatives Considered

### Alternative 1: Gym-Centered Model

A gym-centered model would work for some fitness use cases but would not support solo trainers, remote coaches, non-fitness providers, or creator communities.

Rejected because the platform must support multiple community types.

### Alternative 2: Class-Only Groups

Class-based groups are useful, but they are only one form of community.

Rejected because the platform must support communities that exist outside scheduled activities.

### Alternative 3: General Community Primitive

Accepted because it supports many forms of social and commercial organization.

## Consequences

### Positive Consequences

- Supports trainer-led communities.
- Supports gyms and businesses.
- Supports client groups.
- Supports creator audiences.
- Supports future social network features.
- Supports community-based offers, activities, and referrals.
- Supports many industries.

### Negative Consequences

- Requires thoughtful permission rules.
- Requires community role management.
- Requires moderation decisions later.
- Requires clarity between organizations and communities.

## Cross-Industry Impact

This model supports:

- Trainers creating client communities
- Therapists creating support or practice communities
- Tutors creating student cohorts
- Music teachers creating studio groups
- Tattoo artists creating customer followings
- Coaches creating program groups
- Consultants creating client communities
- Creators creating audience communities

The same primitive can support many social and commercial patterns.

## Scale Impact

### 1,000 Active Users

Communities can support simple client groups, gym groups, and cohorts.

### 10,000 Active Users

Communities can support memberships, discussions, events, and referral loops.

### 100,000 Active Users

Communities become a core platform graph for discovery, reputation, commerce, and retention.

### Multiple Vertical Applications

Each application can create industry-specific community experiences on top of the same primitive.

### Third-Party Developers

Developers can build applications around communities without needing to rebuild membership, roles, or participation models.

## AI Review Summary

AI coding tools must not model communities only as gyms, classes, or trainer groups inside platform-core.

When a feature involves groups, cohorts, audiences, memberships, local networks, or shared participation, AI tools must evaluate whether it belongs in the generalized `Community` primitive.

## Final Decision

Accepted.

The platform will use a generalized `Community` primitive and community membership model. Famm may expose fitness-specific community labels in the application layer, but platform-core will remain industry-neutral.
